<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Description</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="supplementary description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Supplementary description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
Male head with median dark brown marking covering frons and ocellar areas. Pronotum disc with median brown band, medially pale with light rugosities, margins dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7871740" captionText="Figure 5. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia dorsolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681199" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">5</figureCitation>
A). Mesonotum and metanotum with dark U-shaped marking. Tergum 9 anteriorly with prominent transverse ridge (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7871740" captionText="Figure 5. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia dorsolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681199" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">5</figureCitation>
B). Tergum 10 divided medially, forming sclerotised shield-like structure. Epiproct wide and elliptical, medially slightly upraised, sides with upward dark margins from base to basal half dorsally; then gradually tapering to sharp apex, apically narrow and thread-like, bending backwards forming hook-shaped structure (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7871740" captionText="Figure 5. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia dorsolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681199" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">5</figureCitation>
B and Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F7871744" captionText="Figure 6. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Male A epiproct dorsal view; B epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681200" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">6</figureCitation>
A). Laterally sclerotised, constricted from base to basal half, then curved outwards, apically back-curved and forming hook-shaped apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F7871740" captionText="Figure 5. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Male A head and pronotum; B terminalia dorsal view; C terminalia dorsolateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681199" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">5</figureCitation>
C and Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F7871744" captionText="Figure 6. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Male A epiproct dorsal view; B epiproct lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681200" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">6</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="female">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Female</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
Body length 9.0-9.5 mm, forewing length 8.0-8.5 mm, hind-wing length 7.0-8.0 mm (n = 4). Habitus generally similar to male (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7871748" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Female A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681201" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">7</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergum stripes same as male, except for tergum 8 with median brown elliptical mark; lateral dark patches present anteriorly on segments 2-4. Posterior margin of sternum 8 bears large rounded subgenital plate ventrally, reaching near to half of sternum 9. Subgenital plate posteromedially bears lobe-like structure, seems like U-shaped narrow patch and covered with many hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7871748" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Female A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681201" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">7</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">China, Sichuan Province, Wanglang National Nature Reserve.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">
This species was established by 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen, Z. T." journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" pagination="291 - 293" refId="B7871501" refString="Chen, Z. T., Du, Y. Z., 2017. A new species of Sweltsa (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae) from China, with a key to the Sweltsa males of China. Zootaxa 4337 (2): 291 - 293" title="A new species of Sweltsa (Plecoptera: Chloroperlidae) from China, with a key to the Sweltsa males of China" volume="4337" year="2017">Chen and Du (2017)</bibRefCitation>
. They did not provide any closely-related species maybe because this species is easily distinguishable from all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ricker" authorityYear="1943" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Sweltsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the epiproct backward hook. However, here we can add that this species epiproct structure is partially similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zhiltzova &amp; Levanidova" authorityYear="1978" class="Insecta" family="Chloroperlidae" genus="Sweltsa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sweltsa illiesi" order="Plecoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="illiesi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">Sweltsa illiesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Zhiltzova &amp; Levanidova, 1978 (
<bibRefCitation author="Teslenko, V. A." journalOrPublisher="University of Illinois Press Urbana and Chicago" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" pagination=": 382 pp" refId="B7871672" refString="Teslenko, V. A., Zhiltzova, L. A., 2009. Key to the stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and adjacent countries. In: Imagines and nymphs. Dalnauka, Vladivostok,.: 382 pp" title="Key to the stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and adjacent countries" volumeTitle="Imagines and nymphs. Dalnauka, Vladivostok,." year="2009">Teslenko and Zhiltzova 2009</bibRefCitation>
) in general appearance and can be easily distinguished from this species by the epiproct backward hook. Besides this, we also describe the female of this species, which is not reported in the original description. The female subgenital plate of the 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. hamula" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="hamula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. hamula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species is wide, rounded and posteromedially bears a small U-shaped patch and is covered with hairs (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7871748" captionText="Figure 7. Sweltsa hamula Chen &amp; Du, 2017. Female A head and pronotum; B terminalia ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e86347.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/681201" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">7</figureCitation>
B). In contrast, the subgenital plate of 
<taxonomicName genus="S." lsidName="S. illiesi" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347" rank="species" species="illiesi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="86347">S. illiesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is subtriangular and medially with a round patch and margin of the plate is covered with hairs (fig. 520 in Teslenko &amp; Zhiltzova 2009). These features easily distinguish female of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
</subSection>
